<div id="review_2739995062" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2739995062" />
    <a title="Luke Walker" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8771996-luke-walker"><img alt="Luke Walker" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1639714640p2/8771996.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2739995062?book_show_action=true">Jul 24, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Luke Walker" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Luke Walker" href="/user/show/8771996-luke-walker">Luke Walker</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2739995062" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14692670662646517514">7.8/10 In my opinion, Greg Iles books are very readable and I get into them very quickly. I enjoy that the Penn Cage series is set in Natchez, which I am familiar with. Penn Cage is a great character, but I may like his Dad even more, though he doesn’t play as much of a role in this one as in some of the others. The only criticism could have about this book is that it has many of the same beats that his other Natchez books have. Some may find it redundant, but I don’t mind it.</span>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

